1
00:00:36,460 --> 00:00:38,769
(Recording of opera music plays)

2
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:49,731
(Footsteps)

3
00:00:54,300 --> 00:00:55,780
(Knock at door)

4
00:01:07,621 --> 00:01:08,974
You weren't followed?

5
00:01:09,861 --> 00:01:11,259
No.

6
00:01:11,380 --> 00:01:13,132
Better come in.

7
00:01:17,381 --> 00:01:20,054
Trust no one, Jim.

8
00:01:20,181 --> 00:01:22,138
Especially not in the mainstream.

9
00:01:27,341 --> 00:01:28,819
Sit down.

10
00:01:40,580 --> 00:01:45,499
I understand you still have
one Hungarian identity running?

11
00:01:46,621 --> 00:01:48,054
I do.

12
00:01:54,261 --> 00:01:56,252
I want you to go to Budapest.

13
00:01:58,541 --> 00:02:01,102
This is not above board.

14
00:02:01,222 --> 00:02:03,178
Nobody else knows.

15
00:02:04,942 --> 00:02:07,090
They're after my head, Jim boy.

16
00:02:08,700 --> 00:02:10,373
Do you understand?

17
00:02:33,103 --> 00:02:36,013
I have had an offer of service.

18
00:02:38,061 --> 00:02:41,417
A Hungarian general
wants to come over.

19
00:02:42,742 --> 00:02:44,778
I would like you to meet him.

20
00:02:47,743 --> 00:02:50,892
He has some information
that I need, Jim.

21
00:02:52,982 --> 00:02:54,893
What information?

22
00:02:56,702 --> 00:02:58,216
Treasure.

23
00:03:01,263 --> 00:03:03,696
He has the name of the mole...

24
00:03:03,822 --> 00:03:07,337
the Russians have planted
in the British intelligence service...

25
00:03:07,462 --> 00:03:10,261
right at the top of the Circus.

26
00:03:15,223 --> 00:03:18,657
There's a rotten apple, Jim.

27
00:03:18,781 --> 00:03:20,773
We have to find it.

28
00:03:56,703 --> 00:03:58,499
(♪ Jazz)

29
00:04:35,864 --> 00:04:38,617
(Rumbling)

30
00:04:38,744 --> 00:04:41,018
(Clatter)

31
00:05:07,783 --> 00:05:09,421
Stop!

32
00:05:44,385 --> 00:05:47,582
(Clock chimes)

33
00:06:18,904 --> 00:06:22,181
(Control) Would you witness this for me?

34
00:06:22,305 --> 00:06:24,899
I wish I could done more, Control.

35
00:06:25,025 --> 00:06:27,460
You did all you could, Percy.

36
00:06:31,384 --> 00:06:35,936
Well, a man should know
when to leave the party.

37
00:06:39,106 --> 00:06:41,062
What about Smiley?

38
00:06:41,905 --> 00:06:44,261
Smiley is leaving with me.

39
00:07:05,106 --> 00:07:06,858
You little prick, Esterhase.

40
00:09:36,747 --> 00:09:40,058
(Alarm clock)

41
00:10:02,068 --> 00:10:04,218
Gentlemen, shall we start?

42
00:12:18,389 --> 00:12:21,268
(Secretary) Under Secretary Lacon
is ready for you, Sir Percy.

43
00:12:26,111 --> 00:12:27,544
The Treasury don't understand.

44
00:12:27,671 --> 00:12:30,743
Why can't the intelligence service
simply put in a request

45
00:12:30,871 --> 00:12:32,382
for a general increase in funding

46
00:12:32,509 --> 00:12:35,308
and then you account
for the spend on your special operation?

47
00:12:36,390 --> 00:12:39,029
Operation Witchcraft
needs to remain secret.

48
00:12:39,150 --> 00:12:41,984
- It's a fiefdom of its own.
- Yes, that's what's worrying us.

49
00:12:42,111 --> 00:12:44,625
The whole thing.
very unaccountable, isn't it?

50
00:12:46,230 --> 00:12:49,745
And this London house
that nobody knows the address of,

51
00:12:49,870 --> 00:12:51,429
is that really necessary?

52
00:12:51,551 --> 00:12:54,782
Now more than ever.
We need to protect our Soviet source.

53
00:12:54,911 --> 00:12:58,461
So where do you propose we meet?
In a café?

54
00:12:58,592 --> 00:13:01,184
The rent and rates on this house
have doubled.

55
00:13:02,551 --> 00:13:05,269
We spent millions on nuclear warheads.

56
00:13:05,390 --> 00:13:08,144
We're asking
for a few thousand for a house.

57
00:13:08,271 --> 00:13:10,148
I wonder if Karla has the same problem

58
00:13:10,271 --> 00:13:11,943
with the Treasury at the Kremlin.

59
00:13:12,071 --> 00:13:13,505
Look, nobody underestimates

60
00:13:13,630 --> 00:13:16,144
the importance of the job
you chaps are doing.

61
00:13:16,270 --> 00:13:18,466
But what happened
in Budapest last year,

62
00:13:20,431 --> 00:13:22,183
that was a disaster.

63
00:13:22,311 --> 00:13:24,143
With respect, sir,

64
00:13:24,272 --> 00:13:27,184
it wasn't one of your civil servants
that got killed, was it?

65
00:13:27,312 --> 00:13:29,620
Now this isn't about soldiers
in trenches any more.

66
00:13:29,751 --> 00:13:31,946
- We're the front line now...
- Roy!

67
00:13:32,071 --> 00:13:35,303
For 25 years we've been the only thing
standing between them and Karla

68
00:13:35,432 --> 00:13:37,582
and Moscow
and the third bloody world war.

69
00:13:39,712 --> 00:13:42,668
Look, the Minister's very pleased
with your progress so far.

70
00:13:44,671 --> 00:13:46,343
He's less pleased, though,

71
00:13:46,471 --> 00:13:48,939
with the lack of progress
with our American cousins.

72
00:13:50,552 --> 00:13:51,905
You see,

73
00:13:52,032 --> 00:13:54,023
in their eyes,

74
00:13:54,152 --> 00:13:56,460
you're still a leaky ship.

75
00:14:10,151 --> 00:14:11,505
(Buzzer)

76
00:14:13,991 --> 00:14:14,901
Yes?

77
00:14:15,031 --> 00:14:17,944
Someone on the line for you, sir.
Seems urgent.

78
00:14:18,072 --> 00:14:19,744
All right, well put him through.

79
00:14:19,872 --> 00:14:21,305
(Phone rings)

80
00:14:21,432 --> 00:14:24,741
- Hello?
- Is this Under Secretary Lacon?

81
00:14:24,871 --> 00:14:26,145
Yes.

82
00:14:26,271 --> 00:14:28,388
My name's Ricki Tarr.

83
00:14:29,632 --> 00:14:31,748
- What do you want?
- I need to meet you.

84
00:14:32,913 --> 00:14:36,189
If you need to confirm who I am,
you can talk to my boss at the Circus,

85
00:14:36,313 --> 00:14:37,984
Peter Guillam.

86
00:14:38,112 --> 00:14:40,626
But only Guillam, no one else.

87
00:14:54,632 --> 00:14:56,111
You got clearance for that?

88
00:14:56,232 --> 00:14:58,985
Well, I'm not bloody
chaining it up outside.

89
00:14:59,112 --> 00:15:01,627
Mind you, no better off in here
with this bunch of bloody cut-throats.

90
00:15:01,753 --> 00:15:04,221
They'd have the gold out of your teeth.

91
00:15:04,353 --> 00:15:07,742
Thought I'd pop in and catch a glimpse
of the new girl before Bland gets to her.

92
00:15:07,872 --> 00:15:11,070
Ah, yes. Belinda the blonde.

93
00:15:11,193 --> 00:15:13,149
- Has he seen her yet?
- Of course he has.

94
00:15:13,273 --> 00:15:14,911
Came down first thing this morning.

95
00:15:15,033 --> 00:15:16,672
Belinda.

96
00:15:17,514 --> 00:15:18,865
(Rings bicycle bell)

97
00:15:22,992 --> 00:15:24,983
(Phone rings)

98
00:15:26,113 --> 00:15:29,185
- Peter Guillam.
- Hello, Peter, this is Oliver.

99
00:15:29,313 --> 00:15:31,782
Just ringing to find out...

100
00:15:31,914 --> 00:15:35,222
(Joan Bakewell on radio) So Winston
Churchill saved your life, Edie.

101
00:15:35,352 --> 00:15:37,913
(Edie) I was working in the kitchen,
getting dinner ready.

102
00:15:38,033 --> 00:15:39,671
And he was late, you see.

103
00:15:39,793 --> 00:15:42,069
- During a raid?
- During a raid, you see.

104
00:15:42,194 --> 00:15:43,946
He said,
Why aren't you in that shelter?

105
00:15:44,074 --> 00:15:45,553
- Why weren't you?
- Well, because...

106
00:15:55,154 --> 00:15:58,590
(Guillam) I was sorry to hear
about Control, Mr. Smiley.

107
00:16:10,434 --> 00:16:13,232
He said Tarr called him
from a phone box.

108
00:16:21,754 --> 00:16:24,587
He said there's a mole,

109
00:16:26,475 --> 00:16:28,862
right at the top of the Circus,

110
00:16:30,154 --> 00:16:32,462
that he's been there for years.

111
00:16:48,594 --> 00:16:50,391
(Clears throat)

112
00:16:52,315 --> 00:16:53,907
It does mean

113
00:16:54,035 --> 00:16:56,831
you're rather well placed
to look into this matter for us now,

114
00:16:56,954 --> 00:16:58,945
doesn't it?

115
00:16:59,954 --> 00:17:01,626
Outside the family.

116
00:17:10,673 --> 00:17:12,743
I'm retired, Oliver.

117
00:17:12,873 --> 00:17:14,944
You fired me.

118
00:17:15,074 --> 00:17:16,871
The thing is,

119
00:17:16,994 --> 00:17:18,872
some time ago before Control died,

120
00:17:18,995 --> 00:17:21,429
he came to me
with a similar suggestion.

121
00:17:22,715 --> 00:17:24,705
That there is a mole.

122
00:17:27,674 --> 00:17:29,745
He never mentioned
his suspicions to you?

123
00:17:32,075 --> 00:17:33,064
No.

124
00:17:33,195 --> 00:17:36,632
Oh, I just thought that
as you were his man, so to speak...

125
00:17:36,756 --> 00:17:39,029
What did you say to him?

126
00:17:39,154 --> 00:17:41,793
I'm afraid I thought his paranoia
had rather gotten the better of him

127
00:17:41,914 --> 00:17:44,792
and he was going to pull
his whole house down.

128
00:17:44,914 --> 00:17:46,906
That bloody mess in Budapest.

129
00:17:51,156 --> 00:17:53,065
Damn it, George.

130
00:17:53,194 --> 00:17:55,150
It's your generation, your legacy.

131
00:17:56,995 --> 00:17:59,748
I would have thought, if there.
any truth in it, you'd want to...

132
00:18:29,676 --> 00:18:31,473
I'll keep Peter.

133
00:18:32,836 --> 00:18:36,032
And there's a retired
Special Branch man, Mendel.

134
00:18:37,155 --> 00:18:39,147
I should like to have him.

135
00:18:40,276 --> 00:18:41,391
(Scraping)

136
00:18:41,516 --> 00:18:43,427
- Lift up.
- (Buzzing)

137
00:18:47,555 --> 00:18:49,148
And quickly down again.

138
00:18:53,075 --> 00:18:56,352
There's a place I know, sir.
A little hotel near Liverpool Street.

139
00:19:00,397 --> 00:19:01,350
(Buzzing)

140
00:19:10,356 --> 00:19:11,756
(Whirring)

141
00:19:11,877 --> 00:19:13,435
(Buzzing)

142
00:19:28,517 --> 00:19:32,953
Be careful with it. Please.
It's Georgian.

143
00:19:33,076 --> 00:19:36,705
My friend wants peace and quiet
in order to work, Mrs. Pope Graham.

144
00:19:36,836 --> 00:19:37,906
No disturbances.

145
00:19:38,757 --> 00:19:41,225
Her real name is just Graham.

146
00:19:41,357 --> 00:19:43,392
Added the Pope for a touch of class.

147
00:19:57,316 --> 00:20:01,434
(Smiley) Peter, did you get the keys
to Control's flat?

148
00:20:06,997 --> 00:20:12,673
♪ And did those feet in ancient time

149
00:20:12,796 --> 00:20:16,915
♪ Walk upon England.
mountains green?

150
00:20:19,397 --> 00:20:20,547
Oh!

151
00:21:45,198 --> 00:21:46,188
(Control) George!

152
00:21:48,157 --> 00:21:49,556
George, get in here!

153
00:21:53,718 --> 00:21:55,549
George.

154
00:21:56,999 --> 00:21:59,149
Sit down.

155
00:22:04,238 --> 00:22:06,308
Take a look at this nonsense.

156
00:22:11,159 --> 00:22:12,593
Report by Soviet high command

157
00:22:12,720 --> 00:22:16,427
on their recent naval exercises
in the Black Sea.

158
00:22:16,558 --> 00:22:19,072
Just what the admiralty
has been begging us

159
00:22:19,198 --> 00:22:20,836
for some information on.

160
00:22:22,078 --> 00:22:24,070
- Where did you get this?
- I didn't.

161
00:22:24,199 --> 00:22:26,030
Percy and his little cabal
walked in with it.

162
00:22:26,159 --> 00:22:28,151
- Look, Control...
- Shut up.

163
00:22:28,960 --> 00:22:31,153
Style appalling.

164
00:22:31,278 --> 00:22:34,157
Patently a fabrication
from beginning to end.

165
00:22:34,279 --> 00:22:38,238
- Just could be the real thing.
- Well, if it's genuine, it's gold dust.

166
00:22:39,200 --> 00:22:41,919
But its topicality makes it suspect.

167
00:22:42,040 --> 00:22:45,190
Smiley is suspicious, Percy.

168
00:22:45,319 --> 00:22:48,038
Where did it come from?
What's the access?

169
00:22:48,159 --> 00:22:50,116
A new secret source of mine.

170
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:51,832
But how could he
possibly have access?

171
00:22:51,960 --> 00:22:54,997
He has access to the most sensitive
levels of policy-making.

172
00:22:56,800 --> 00:22:58,356
We've named the operation Witchcraft.

173
00:22:58,478 --> 00:23:01,277
Oh, Percy and his pals
bypassed us, Smiley.

174
00:23:01,399 --> 00:23:03,515
Gone straight to the minister.

175
00:23:03,639 --> 00:23:07,713
Percy has been allowed to keep
the identity of his new friend

176
00:23:07,840 --> 00:23:09,239
top secret.

177
00:23:09,360 --> 00:23:12,795
The minister agrees too many secrets
are blown around here.

178
00:23:12,919 --> 00:23:14,750
Too much failure,
too many scandals.

179
00:23:14,879 --> 00:23:18,077
- Too little solid intelligence.
- Percy does have a point, Control.

180
00:23:18,200 --> 00:23:20,760
We should be fighting Communism,
not each other.

181
00:23:20,880 --> 00:23:23,475
Meanwhile we're losing our reputation,
our partners.

182
00:23:23,601 --> 00:23:24,827
Your bloody Yanks!

183
00:23:24,959 --> 00:23:27,269
We've had enough!
There's going to be changes.

184
00:23:27,400 --> 00:23:31,028
We need to decide if want to be
part of the past or part of the future.

185
00:23:31,159 --> 00:23:34,152
I should have left you
where I found you.

186
00:23:34,280 --> 00:23:36,236
- Look!
- Control...

187
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:38,033
Out, all of you!

188
00:23:59,961 --> 00:24:03,077
If Witchcraft is genuine...

189
00:24:03,200 --> 00:24:05,396
(Control) Nothing is genuine any more.

190
00:24:22,440 --> 00:24:23,953
(Guillam) George...

191
00:24:27,721 --> 00:24:30,713
Do you want me to get
this stuff over to the hotel?

192
00:24:42,321 --> 00:24:44,312
(Train passing)

193
00:24:50,040 --> 00:24:52,156
Thank you.
Uh, anywhere will do.

194
00:24:54,041 --> 00:24:55,360
- Peter?
- Hm?

195
00:24:55,481 --> 00:24:57,757
I need you to do something for me.

196
00:25:07,001 --> 00:25:08,879
I'd like you to go to the Circus.

197
00:25:11,402 --> 00:25:14,360
In the cabinet
at the duty officers' station

198
00:25:14,482 --> 00:25:16,630
are records of staff recently retired.

199
00:25:19,641 --> 00:25:21,552
I'd like photographs of them

200
00:25:21,681 --> 00:25:25,880
and of the diagram of the Circus.
reorganisation under Percy Alleline,

201
00:25:26,762 --> 00:25:30,515
along with a list of all payments
made from the Reptile fund.

202
00:26:02,162 --> 00:26:05,438
- Help you with anything, Bill?
- I was just looking for his Majesty.

203
00:26:05,562 --> 00:26:07,633
Well, he's out walking the battlements.

204
00:26:10,363 --> 00:26:11,714
Oh.

205
00:26:11,841 --> 00:26:13,673
(Speaks Hungarian)

206
00:26:45,283 --> 00:26:49,322
- Heard you had an accident, Peter.
- Yeah, I cut my hand open on a drawer.

207
00:26:49,443 --> 00:26:52,038
When are you going
to get some new furniture up here?

208
00:26:54,762 --> 00:26:58,152
I'll have a word with Esterhase.
We'll make it a priority on the top floor.

209
00:26:59,762 --> 00:27:01,560
- Where are you off to?
- Lunch.

210
00:27:03,843 --> 00:27:05,595
Want some company?

211
00:27:06,604 --> 00:27:08,558
(Guillam)
According to the personnel files,

212
00:27:08,682 --> 00:27:10,240
seven were due for retirement anyway.

213
00:27:10,362 --> 00:27:12,479
Another four don't seem
particularly mysterious.

214
00:27:12,603 --> 00:27:15,481
Jerry Westerby was dismissed
December 4.

215
00:27:16,603 --> 00:27:18,401
Connie Sachs retired November 28.

216
00:27:18,524 --> 00:27:21,559
That's just two weeks
after you and Control were forced out.

217
00:27:30,844 --> 00:27:33,483
- Return to Oxford, please.
- That's 1.15.

218
00:27:51,363 --> 00:27:54,162
Percy has always resisted
any proposal

219
00:27:54,284 --> 00:27:57,913
of a wider exploitation
of Witchcraft's intelligence.

220
00:27:58,044 --> 00:27:59,842
Drop the bloody jargon, Lacon.

221
00:27:59,965 --> 00:28:02,682
I've refused to share Witchcraft
with our allies so far, Minister.

222
00:28:04,043 --> 00:28:05,762
Greedy boy.

223
00:28:05,884 --> 00:28:09,193
My goal has been to establish
its track record beyond all doubt.

224
00:28:13,204 --> 00:28:16,798
I think the time has come to approach
our American brothers-in-arms.

225
00:28:19,243 --> 00:28:23,123
- Will they take us back into bed?
- I'm not interested in a one-off trade.

226
00:28:23,244 --> 00:28:27,557
I want on-going access
to American intelligence.

227
00:28:27,685 --> 00:28:29,198
You think we can get it?

228
00:28:29,325 --> 00:28:32,953
With Witchcraft on our side, we can
get anything we bloody well want.

229
00:28:37,165 --> 00:28:38,484
Fine.

230
00:28:39,405 --> 00:28:40,474
Carry on.

231
00:28:43,645 --> 00:28:45,042
Thank you.

232
00:28:56,005 --> 00:28:58,518
(Male actor) And I strike thee down...

233
00:29:23,165 --> 00:29:24,234
Oh, I, uh...

234
00:29:28,004 --> 00:29:30,997
Not supposed to.
Doctor's orders.

235
00:29:33,645 --> 00:29:35,476
Wicked, wicked George.

236
00:29:56,604 --> 00:29:58,482
I don't know about you, George,

237
00:29:58,605 --> 00:30:01,039
but I feel seriously under-fucked.

238
00:30:04,686 --> 00:30:06,802
I heard Ann left you again.

239
00:30:09,005 --> 00:30:12,395
She doesn't deserve you, George,
not one hair on your head.

240
00:30:12,525 --> 00:30:16,644
You left the Circus
shortly after I retired.

241
00:30:17,926 --> 00:30:21,078
I didn't leave. I was dismissed.

242
00:30:21,207 --> 00:30:24,881
Chucked out on the rubbish heap,
like you.

243
00:30:25,005 --> 00:30:25,994
Why?

244
00:30:31,206 --> 00:30:32,321
(Connie) Polyakov.

245
00:30:33,406 --> 00:30:35,204
Do you remember him?

246
00:30:36,565 --> 00:30:38,396
(Smiley) From the Soviet Embassy?

247
00:30:38,525 --> 00:30:42,314
(Connie) Alexsey Polyakov,
cultural attaché here in London.

248
00:30:43,486 --> 00:30:47,526
When he arrived here 15 years ago,
I requested he be checked out.

249
00:30:48,647 --> 00:30:52,161
He was graded whiter than white.
Didn't put a foot wrong.

250
00:30:53,406 --> 00:30:55,237
(Smiley) But you disagreed?

251
00:30:55,366 --> 00:30:57,085
(Connie) There's a story
you must have heard

252
00:30:57,207 --> 00:31:00,039
that Karla has set up a secret cell.

253
00:31:00,166 --> 00:31:02,044
The personnel are all ex-military,

254
00:31:02,167 --> 00:31:06,078
trained to handle
deep-penetration agents, moles.

255
00:31:06,205 --> 00:31:08,879
(Smiley) There are always stories,
Connie.

256
00:31:09,006 --> 00:31:11,440
(Connie)
But what if this story was true?

257
00:31:13,247 --> 00:31:16,956
