(Tweeting)

339
00:38:26,334 --> 00:38:28,209
- (Bones crack)
- Ohh!

340
00:38:41,692 --> 00:38:42,966
Come here.

341
00:38:47,373 --> 00:38:50,524
- What's your name?
- Roach. Bill Roach, sir.

342
00:38:50,653 --> 00:38:53,168
- I'm a new boy.
- New arrival, eh?

343
00:38:53,294 --> 00:38:56,284
- What's the story?
- My mother and father.

344
00:38:57,453 --> 00:39:00,206
My father left, so...

345
00:39:00,333 --> 00:39:01,607
Hm.

346
00:39:03,254 --> 00:39:05,051
Bill.

347
00:39:05,174 --> 00:39:06,811
The unpaid Bill.

348
00:39:08,254 --> 00:39:11,164
- Anyone ever call you that?
- No, sir.

349
00:39:11,292 --> 00:39:13,284
Known a lot of Bills in my time.

350
00:39:15,293 --> 00:39:17,329
They've all been good 'uns.

351
00:39:19,574 --> 00:39:21,246
What are you good at?

352
00:39:21,374 --> 00:39:22,853
Nothing, sir.

353
00:39:22,974 --> 00:39:25,692
You're a good watcher, though, eh?

354
00:39:26,573 --> 00:39:28,211
Us loners always are.

355
00:39:33,654 --> 00:39:36,328
Best watcher in the unit,
Bill Roach is, I'll bet.

356
00:39:37,653 --> 00:39:40,929
- Long as he's got his specs on. Right?
- Yes, sir.

357
00:39:42,253 --> 00:39:44,244
This is good, very good.

358
00:41:05,855 --> 00:41:07,334
Hello, Ricki.

359
00:41:14,574 --> 00:41:16,486
You've missed the wedge.

360
00:41:23,576 --> 00:41:25,611
Where have you been, Ricki?

361
00:41:28,176 --> 00:41:30,165
They're going to kill me.

362
00:41:32,335 --> 00:41:34,610
- Who is?
- Your lot.

363
00:41:34,735 --> 00:41:36,966
Or their lot.
Whoever gets me first.

364
00:41:39,696 --> 00:41:41,971
I'm innocent.

365
00:41:42,096 --> 00:41:43,528
Within reason.

366
00:41:45,335 --> 00:41:47,132
How long have you been here?

367
00:41:47,255 --> 00:41:50,054
Sorry, I've run out of places now.

368
00:41:50,176 --> 00:41:52,007
I needed to see you.

369
00:41:52,897 --> 00:41:54,296
Why?

370
00:41:56,135 --> 00:41:58,012
There's a woman.

371
00:41:59,416 --> 00:42:02,805
I need you to trade for her.
I need you to get her back off Karla.

372
00:42:05,976 --> 00:42:07,534
A woman?

373
00:42:09,777 --> 00:42:12,130
Her name's Irina.

374
00:42:12,255 --> 00:42:13,608
(Ship's horn)

375
00:42:15,896 --> 00:42:17,966
(Tarr) This was last November.

376
00:42:18,096 --> 00:42:22,727
Mr. Guillam sent me to Istanbul
to check out a Russian trade delegate

377
00:42:22,857 --> 00:42:24,686
who might be persuaded to defect.

378
00:42:24,815 --> 00:42:27,535
- (Smiley) Tufty Thesinger, resident.
- Yeah.

379
00:42:27,656 --> 00:42:29,055
- Hiya, Ricki.
- All right, mate?

380
00:42:29,176 --> 00:42:32,647
(Tarr) Did you know him?
(Smiley) No, never met him.

381
00:42:32,777 --> 00:42:34,414
(Tarr) Bit of a drinker.

382
00:42:34,536 --> 00:42:36,050
Hangover from hell.

383
00:42:36,177 --> 00:42:38,166
Bit of a fucking idiot.

384
00:42:40,415 --> 00:42:42,247
Apparently this Russian,
name of Boris,

385
00:42:42,376 --> 00:42:44,685
was spending high and wide
in the nightclubs.

386
00:42:44,816 --> 00:42:47,285
(Smiley) So you were sent
to persuade this Boris?

387
00:42:47,417 --> 00:42:50,648
(Tarr) Yeah.
He was your typical Russian.

388
00:42:50,777 --> 00:42:53,768
Trade delegation by day,
out boozing every night.

389
00:42:53,896 --> 00:42:55,693
Didn't seem to sleep.

390
00:42:55,816 --> 00:42:57,853
Tufty was worn out
from following him around.

391
00:42:57,977 --> 00:43:00,730
I think it's going to be
a long night, son.

392
00:43:00,857 --> 00:43:03,531
(Tarr) His favourite haunt
was this club in Taksim.

393
00:43:03,658 --> 00:43:07,969
It had a hellhole in the basement
where the sailors and the tourists went.

394
00:43:09,456 --> 00:43:13,416
Anyway, I took one look at him
and I knew I'd wasted a journey.

395
00:43:15,537 --> 00:43:17,175
Boris was no delegate.

396
00:43:18,538 --> 00:43:22,006
What delegate bothers
to play drunker than he really is?

397
00:43:23,256 --> 00:43:26,010
You get to recognise your own,
don't you, Mr. Smiley?

398
00:43:26,137 --> 00:43:27,809
And Boris was a hood.

399
00:43:27,937 --> 00:43:29,451
(♪ BLOOD, SWEAT & TEARS:
Spinning Wheel)

400
00:43:29,578 --> 00:43:31,614
Moscow Centre trained.

401
00:43:31,738 --> 00:43:34,125
♪ Someone is waiting

402
00:43:34,256 --> 00:43:35,975
♪ I mean just for you

403
00:43:36,657 --> 00:43:38,295
♪ Spinning wheel

404
00:43:38,417 --> 00:43:41,728
♪ Keep on spinning through,
Drop all your troubles... ♪

405
00:43:41,858 --> 00:43:44,451
I guessed he was waiting
for a connect.

406
00:43:46,178 --> 00:43:48,406
Working a letterbox, maybe.

407
00:43:48,536 --> 00:43:52,928
Or trailing his coat and looking
for a pass from some mug like me.

408
00:43:53,057 --> 00:43:56,130
So the second night
I went to the import/export outfit

409
00:43:56,258 --> 00:44:00,695
that Tufty had set up with
a cipher room hidden in the back.

410
00:44:00,818 --> 00:44:03,775
I cabled No sale to Mr. Guillam.

411
00:44:04,857 --> 00:44:06,769
And that was that.

412
00:44:08,218 --> 00:44:10,288
(Smiley) You were due
to fly home the next day.

413
00:44:10,418 --> 00:44:11,818
Yes.

414
00:44:13,699 --> 00:44:15,369
But you didn't.

415
00:44:28,339 --> 00:44:30,453
(Tarr) Boris had a wife.

416
00:44:30,577 --> 00:44:31,976
Common-law.

417
00:44:32,817 --> 00:44:36,731
Apparently she was a member
of the delegation in her own right.

418
00:45:32,299 --> 00:45:35,769
You once told me to trust my instincts
about women, Mr. Smiley.

419
00:45:37,059 --> 00:45:40,368
Well, my instincts told me
this woman had some treasure.

420
00:45:44,099 --> 00:45:48,651
When Boris went out for the night,
I found myself going into her hotel.

421
00:45:48,780 --> 00:45:50,577
(Smiley) So you dropped Boris.

422
00:45:50,700 --> 00:45:53,896
(Tarr) I know.
It was breaking protocol.

423
00:45:55,299 --> 00:45:59,054
But I was acting on my own initiative,
as it were.

424
00:45:59,180 --> 00:46:02,013
Your man's a bit of a bastard, isn't he?

425
00:46:02,140 --> 00:46:05,132
I just wanted to make sure
you were all right, OK?

426
00:46:05,260 --> 00:46:07,294
(Smiley) So you didn't come home?

427
00:46:08,538 --> 00:46:11,292
I would have.

428
00:46:11,419 --> 00:46:13,455
Boris was a dead end, but...

429
00:46:15,500 --> 00:46:16,819
Um...

430
00:46:17,500 --> 00:46:18,728
I could...

431
00:46:19,980 --> 00:46:22,777
I could sense something in her.

432
00:46:23,979 --> 00:46:26,130
A secret.

433
00:46:26,260 --> 00:46:31,460
And how did you intend
to get this secret out of her?

434
00:46:38,499 --> 00:46:41,332
(Tarr) I played this businessman,
Michael Trench.

435
00:46:45,580 --> 00:46:47,173
Holiday romance.

436
00:46:47,301 --> 00:46:48,891
(She laughs)

437
00:46:51,019 --> 00:46:53,488
I thought I'd take my time with it.

438
00:47:42,262 --> 00:47:44,410
I know who you are.

439
00:47:46,181 --> 00:47:49,058
I want to talk to your boss.

440
00:47:49,180 --> 00:47:50,738
Control.

441
00:47:53,301 --> 00:47:55,735
I have something to trade.

442
00:47:55,861 --> 00:47:57,373
Something big.

443
00:47:58,540 --> 00:48:00,974
I want a new life in the West.

444
00:48:02,541 --> 00:48:04,532
That's the deal.

445
00:48:06,862 --> 00:48:08,659
You tell them.

446
00:48:17,181 --> 00:48:20,731
Look, you can't expect them
to jump at every offer of service.

447
00:48:24,102 --> 00:48:27,854
If you won't tell me more,
there is nothing I can do.

448
00:48:33,261 --> 00:48:35,901
If I tell you everything,

449
00:48:36,022 --> 00:48:37,853
I'm putting my life in your hands.

450
00:48:40,101 --> 00:48:42,092
And the lives of other people.

451
00:49:41,102 --> 00:49:43,901
(Tarr) So she told me
what she had to trade.

452
00:49:45,583 --> 00:49:47,494
Her secret.

453
00:49:47,623 --> 00:49:49,852
I mean,

454
00:49:49,982 --> 00:49:52,052
the mother of all secrets.

455
00:49:55,103 --> 00:49:57,492
I told her I'd alert the Circus.

456
00:49:57,623 --> 00:50:01,060
She made me promise I wouldn.
give any of the details to London.

457
00:50:01,184 --> 00:50:03,980
(Smiley) And you agreed?
(Tarr) Yes.

458
00:50:05,223 --> 00:50:06,780
I mean it was...

459
00:50:06,902 --> 00:50:10,054
I couldn't believe
I'd got hold of something this big.

460
00:50:10,183 --> 00:50:12,856
I went back to the import/export,

461
00:50:12,983 --> 00:50:16,861
sent the message to the Circus,
graded, Flash, highest priority,

462
00:50:16,982 --> 00:50:20,099
just that I had a Moscow-trained hood
wanting to defect.

463
00:50:20,222 --> 00:50:24,853
You're supposed to have gone.
London stations have been on to me.

464
00:50:24,983 --> 00:50:27,179
Want to know what the hell you're doing.

465
00:50:31,863 --> 00:50:33,376
Fuck off.

466
00:50:34,583 --> 00:50:36,461
(Smiley) Anything else, Ricki?

467
00:50:40,743 --> 00:50:43,497
I know what I am to the Circus.
I'm one of the scalp-hunters,

468
00:50:43,624 --> 00:50:46,420
someone that you can hand
your dirty little jobs to.

469
00:50:49,863 --> 00:50:51,342
I just...

470
00:50:52,904 --> 00:50:55,498
I just wanted to bring
this one in myself.

471
00:50:55,624 --> 00:50:57,853
Well, I understand how you felt.

472
00:50:59,983 --> 00:51:02,178
You wanted to do something.

473
00:51:02,303 --> 00:51:04,499
I said that she claimed
to have information

474
00:51:04,624 --> 00:51:07,457
vital to the safeguarding of the Circus.

475
00:51:10,545 --> 00:51:12,181
Anything more?

476
00:51:24,144 --> 00:51:27,692
I said that she had information
concerning a double agent.

477
00:51:30,824 --> 00:51:35,022
Look, I just wanted to get
the proper attention. And I'd...

478
00:51:35,144 --> 00:51:36,624
(Tarr sighs)

479
00:51:36,745 --> 00:51:38,940
I told them this was the reason
why I had not come home.

480
00:51:39,065 --> 00:51:41,259
It wasn't that I'd defected or anything.

481
00:51:42,824 --> 00:51:45,861
- What did you do then?
- I waited for a reply.

482
00:51:51,625 --> 00:51:54,342
(Tarr) I hung around for hours.
I heard the Imsak call to prayer.

483
00:51:54,463 --> 00:51:58,173
So what's that?
That's about 3.30 in the morning.

484
00:51:58,304 --> 00:52:00,534
(Clicking)

485
00:52:00,664 --> 00:52:02,383
Then the message comes through.

486
00:52:06,225 --> 00:52:08,419
'We read you.

487
00:52:10,104 --> 00:52:12,538
That was all they sent. Nothing.

488
00:52:13,425 --> 00:52:16,861
It didn't make sense.
It was like they were stalling.

489
00:52:23,305 --> 00:52:25,135
(Smiley) Then what happened?

490
00:52:25,264 --> 00:52:28,097
(Tarr) Then, all of a sudden...

491
00:52:29,745 --> 00:52:32,100
the Russians begin to move.

492
00:52:33,305 --> 00:52:35,613
(♪ Music on radio)

493
00:52:50,985 --> 00:52:52,577
(Music stops)

494
00:53:04,104 --> 00:53:07,859
It was nice work.
I couldn't have done it better myself.

495
00:53:07,985 --> 00:53:09,384
(Flies buzz)

496
00:53:14,066 --> 00:53:17,853
(Tarr) The message was quite clear.
I needed to warn her.

497
00:53:53,266 --> 00:53:54,780
(Phone rings)

498
00:54:12,305 --> 00:54:14,102
Come on, come on, come on.

499
00:54:28,746 --> 00:54:30,862
(Tarr) I couldn't find her at the airport.

500
00:54:30,986 --> 00:54:33,706
I even looked through
all the flight lists and...

501
00:54:35,427 --> 00:54:37,020
I headed down to the harbour.

502
00:54:47,747 --> 00:54:49,783
They put her on a ship to Odessa.

503
00:54:51,987 --> 00:54:53,785
That's all I know.

504
00:55:03,588 --> 00:55:04,987
I've...

505
00:55:10,027 --> 00:55:13,940
I've done a lot of things in my life,
Mr. Smiley, but...

506
00:55:19,748 --> 00:55:23,182
I just...
I can't stop thinking about her.

507
00:55:27,267 --> 00:55:29,258
She wasn't even my type.

508
00:55:33,308 --> 00:55:35,424
I've got to get her out.
I owe her that.

509
00:55:40,787 --> 00:55:43,860
Karla will be looking for you.

510
00:55:43,988 --> 00:55:46,662
Everybody's looking for me.

511
00:55:49,309 --> 00:55:51,218
You can't stay here.

512
00:55:53,587 --> 00:55:55,145
